( ) (The Hon. Speaker) I wish to inform Parliament that I have received the Determination of the Supreme Court in respect of the Bill
entitled Prevention of Terrorism (Temporary Provisions) (Amendment), which was challenged in the Supreme Court in terms of Article 121(1) of the Constitution.
The Determination of the Supreme Court, as to the constitutionality of the Bill entitled Prevention of Terrorism (Temporary Provisions) (Amendment), is as follows:
(i) Clause 2 of the Bill is not inconsistent with any provision of the Constitution.

(ii) Clause 3 of the Bill cannot be enacted in to law unless the number of votes cast in favour thereof amounts to not less than two-thirds of the whole number of Members (including those not present), as per the Constitution.

The Supreme Court is however of the view that if the provisions in Clause 3 of the Bill are amended as set out in the Determination of the Supreme Court, it would cease to be inconsistent with any provision of the Constitution.

(iii) The Supreme Court states that, be that as it may, the learned Additional Solicitor General has informed the Court that the Hon. Attorney-General would be advising the Minister to insert Article 141 into the body of the proposed Section 10 in Clause 4 of the Bill and that the Minister would move that Amendment at the Committee Stage of Parliament to address the concerns of the Petitioners.
(iv) For the reasons mentioned in the Determination of the Supreme Court, the Supreme Court holds that Clause 5 of the Bill is not inconsistent with any provision of the Constitution.
(v) The Supreme Court holds that Clause 6 cannot inquire into pronounce upon or in any manner

"Ref: Change of Occupant Name and Arrears of Electricity Bills Issued for Residence No. 400/53 M, Sarana Road, Colombo 07
Reference is made to the above subject matter.

I came into occupation at 400/53 M, Sarana Road, Colombo 07 in 2015 approximately around the month of April. The electricity bills that were sent to my residence were paid in full in the first few months. However, when it came to my attention that there is an unusual variance from month to month ranging from approximately 30,000-150,000 LKR and over, I wrote to the CEB seeking clarification and requested the CEB to check the accuracy of the meters to ensure there was no misreading. Regrettably, the CEB did not respond nor took any action with regard to the matter, as a result, there was an accumulation of bills. The position of discrepancy still stands as of date even after many phone conversations seeking clarity have been made subsequent to three letters written to the CEB. Furthermore, I have not been in occupation of the said residence from the month of January, 2022, despite that I have received invoices for the months of January, 2022 and February, 2022 to a total amounting approximately 85,000 LKR, which is so obviously erroneous as nobody was in residence.

In addition to the above matter, I have also brought to the notice of the CEB that the invoices issued for this residence are in the name of a previous resident of the house. This continues to be the status quo to date, as recent as the invoice for the month of February, 2022, despite numerous clarifications and reminders to change the recipients name to my name.

Within the first few months of my occupation of the residence, I wrote to all the institutions and government offices for a change of the name of occupant, which they have all promptly responded and acted upon, except the CEB, resulting in this entire confusion. Given this error, my accountants have advised that they cannot make a tax exemption claim for which I am entitled to, therefore, as a result of the CEB inaction, I stand to involuntarily forego tax exemptions that I am rightfully entitled to. I must also emphasize that if the CEB can address a letter requesting for me to pay the arrears in my name, then, they are obviously aware that I am the new resident at the said address and should not have any issues addressing the invoices in my name.

This unfortunate incident has led to an unnecessary social media and Parliamentary attention directly affecting my reputation and goodwill. It is a fact that there is an outstanding payment due, however, I have taken all steps to rectify the situation while the CEB has not cooperated with any of the efforts made. Due to the negative energy created, I decided to pay Rs. 7.1 million owed to the CEB as an interim solution to the problem. Moreover, I would also like to mention that the receipt I received for the payment of Rs. 7.1 million is also in the previous residents name and not mine. Therefore, I insist that the CEB take necessary action to accept the errors made and rectify the negative consequences that I had to endure created by this situation.
